## What this is

ONE-PARAGRAPH description of the project: what it does, who uses it, the stack, and the
single most important thing to know before changing anything.

## Architecture

- KEY DIRECTORIES and what lives in each (only the non-obvious ones).
- IMPORTANT BOUNDARIES (services, modules, which DB, which API).
- ANYTHING surprising about how the pieces fit (e.g. "two databases — check which one").

## Commands

```bash
# Setup
COMMAND          # install deps / bootstrap

# Develop
COMMAND          # run the dev server / watch

# Test & verify (run before committing)
COMMAND          # unit tests
COMMAND          # lint / type-check / format

# Build
COMMAND          # production build
```

## Conventions

- CODE STYLE that a formatter doesn't already enforce.
- NAMING / FILE LAYOUT patterns to follow.
- TESTING expectations (framework, where tests live, coverage bar).
- COMMIT / PR conventions.

## Working rules

- Read relevant files and follow existing patterns before writing code.
- Make the minimal change that solves the problem; don't refactor unrelated code.
- State assumptions; ask when a decision is genuinely ambiguous.
- DON'T do X (project-specific traps — e.g. "never edit generated files in `gen/`").

## Gotchas

- KNOWN traps, footguns, and "if you see X it means Y" knowledge that isn't in the code.

